than he had in higher education. To my knowledge, I

03:21.317 --> 03:27.524
know that he had been a member of the Board of 
Trustees of the Navasota School District. And Jim

03:27.544 --> 03:31.309
was a big help. I look upon Jim as sort of a student of 
Clyde Freeman's. Clyde Freeman taught James

03:38.315 --> 03:55.238
an immense amount of background information 
regarding the Attorney General's office,

03:38.315 --> 03:55.238
opinions of the Attorney General.

03:57.395 --> 04:06.187
budget procedures, the permanent and available 
university funds, and James was a good student. He

04:06.207 --> 04:07.189
learned them well. They were the main ones. Some of 
your student products in whom you take great

04:11.535 --> 04:20.027
pride, like Brian Cole and others. Yes, yes. My 
number one

04:27.736 --> 04:37.329
choice for a student who who succeeded admirably 
was a chap by the name of Jack Humphreys. Jack came

04:39.372 --> 04:47.323
to me as an assistant registrar at Sam Houston 
State University. I had a call from the president

04:48.745 --> 04:52.630
of that institution saying Frank Have a young man 
over here, assistant registrar. He has a master's

04:58.338 --> 05:00.921
degree in history from Baylor. Really an 
outstanding scholar and student. He's far above

05:04.445 --> 05:07.229
being an assistant registrar. He needs to get his 
doctorate degree and do things other than what

05:07.629 --> 05:13.076
he's doing now. Can you help him? I said, have him 
come over and visit with me. He did. Tremendously

05:18.463 --> 05:21.647
impressive chap. Articulate, poised.

05:26.005 --> 05:38.310
knowledgeable, highly intelligent, excellent

05:26.005 --> 05:38.310
vocabulary,

05:26.005 --> 05:38.310
wrote well.

05:40.889 --> 05:45.437
I asked him to immediately to be a graduate 
assistant in my office. He accepted, later on

05:46.679 --> 06:02.508
became assistant dean, and then associate dean, 
and by the time he finished his PhD degree, he was

05:46.679 --> 06:02.508
truly a remarkable person. I think Jack, had not 
only my high praise, but he was highly respected by

06:06.151 --> 06:25.459
the heads of departments in the college, both of 
liberal arts

06:06.151 --> 06:25.459
and of education.

06:31.160 --> 06:47.382
Jack was astute, tactful, diplomatic in his 
relationships with the administrators in the

06:31.160 --> 06:47.382
colleges and was a tremendously big help. Went 
back to Sam Houston as dean of their liberal arts

06:49.505 --> 06:54.973
section. Stayed a couple of three years there, 
then was chosen by Southern Ross State University

06:55.696 --> 07:02.143
as president. Operated very effectively in that 
office. Revived that institution giving program

07:08.190 --> 07:20.885
by rejuvenating its development foundation and 
was very successful there. Sadly enough, Jack had

07:21.826 --> 07:25.450
cancer. And after a year's stay in Houston on leave 
from Sol Ross, he and his wife and family moved to

07:26.915 --> 07:37.029
Houston with him. He had a wife and two sons. Jack 
died of the cancer. Sad, sad, sad young man.

07:48.384 --> 07:56.635
Another choice of mine was another lad who made 
college presidency, and this was David Johnson, a

07:48.384 --> 07:56.635
Negro from Tyler, who became president of Texas 
College in Tyler, a Methodist-related church,

07:57.678 --> 08:10.073
school, small liberal arts college, struggling 
for survival. David did well, and strangely

08:10.694 --> 08:21.087
enough, too, during

08:10.694 --> 08:21.087
his

08:10.694 --> 08:21.087
term as president, He was identified as a cancer 
patient and died of that disease. So that was sad.

08:29.248 --> 08:34.174
Another one whom I would point to with great pride 
is Linda Whitson. Linda was an outstanding woman

08:35.616 --> 08:42.864
student in the graduate program. Thorough, 
statistically

08:44.766 --> 08:50.753
very sharp, an attractive lady, quite handsome in 
fact, always so well-groomed, articulate, but

08:51.593 --> 09:02.707
quiet. There wasn't an aggressive

09:03.328 --> 09:15.863
inclination, I think, in her makeup, but so 
thorough in the things that she did. After she

09:16.653 --> 09:25.265
received her doctorate, I received a call from the 
president of the University of Texas at San

09:16.653 --> 09:25.265
Antonio asking me about her. She had applied for a 
job over there and was accepted for it and became

09:26.286 --> 09:44.230
vice president at the University of Texas San 
Antonio for

09:26.286 --> 09:44.230
business matters, I think.

09:51.635 --> 09:58.047
Well, a phase of business, personnel matters and 
things of that nature. I don't think she was the

09:58.848 --> 10:14.217
dollar number cruncher, but the area of personnel

09:58.848 --> 10:14.217
relations, she was there and, as I understand, had 
an outstanding record. I would mention those

10:14.618 --> 10:22.789
three as outstanding, along with Brian Cole, who 
also was an associate dean. When he finished with

10:24.111 --> 10:34.625
me, he was

10:24.111 --> 10:34.625
from Marlin, Texas.

10:37.630 --> 10:41.655
Brian came to A&M.

10:45.027 --> 10:48.871
It was he who followed Jack Humphries in the 
office. And Brian was a veteran of the Vietnamese

10:50.172 --> 10:58.240
operation. His undergraduate work had been done 
at the United States Military Academy on the

10:59.121 --> 11:05.828
Hudson, West Point. And just a very, very fine man. 
exceptionally well-trained

11:13.630 --> 11:19.997
individual.

11:23.701 --> 11:36.896
Brian was assistant and then a graduate 
assistant, then assistant dean, then an

11:23.701 --> 11:36.896
associate dean, and

11:23.701 --> 11:36.896
was simply outstanding in the work which he 
performed. Was the immediate past chancellor one

11:38.578 --> 11:43.283
of your doctoral students? Who? The immediate 
past chancellor. Oh, Barry Thompson? Barry. Was

11:51.133 --> 11:52.214
he one of your students? No. I have a connection 
with Barry, but it was not in a student

11:55.659 --> 11:59.464
relationship. These first four that I've 
mentioned, I chaired their doctoral committees.

12:08.635 --> 12:11.419
That's what I perceive you mean by a student. 
Right, right. Barry Thompson was, I knew him

12:12.659 --> 12:19.868
primarily as the son of his father. I knew his 
father quite well. Tommy Thompson,

12:22.111 --> 12:26.036
superintendent of schools at Kermit, Texas for 
many years. A legend among Texas school

12:27.257 --> 12:30.081
administrators. Truly outstanding guy. Barry 
had come up through the public education route.

12:37.169 --> 12:40.033
I'd met him along the way several times. and 
learned from him during a conversation when he

12:40.520 --> 12:54.259
came to campus that he wanted to complete his 
graduate work at A&M. and do a doctorate there with

12:54.779 --> 12:56.581
us. And he says, I've got to find, at that moment, he 
was assistant superintendent of schools for the

12:56.742 --> 13:11.641
Waco Independent School District in charge of 
their curricular matters, assistant

12:56.742 --> 13:11.641
superintendent for curriculum. And his salary, I 
expect, was a pretty good salary at that time. And

13:17.729 --> 13:23.436
he said, Dean Hubert, I simply My family, I would 
put my family to an unjustified position

13:23.872 --> 13:39.015
if I asked them to try to live on the salary of a 
graduate assistant. So if you have anything in the

13:39.035 --> 13:50.031
future that you see developing that you could help 
me in a job here at A&M, I'd appreciate it. Well, I

13:52.542 --> 14:18.718
knew of his high anxiety to finish the doctorate, 
and so there came a time when I was able to upgrade

13:52.542 --> 14:18.718
one of the graduate assistantships associated 
with my office to the point that Barry could live on

13:52.542 --> 14:18.718
it for a year

13:52.542 --> 14:18.718
with his family. And he did, and it was through that 
that he completed his residency at A&M. He already

14:24.590 --> 14:37.848
was a student, commuting student, but he had to 
have a year's residency, and it was my finding him

14:24.590 --> 14:37.848
that position that enabled him to complete that. 
So that was my basic association with him. I did not

14:44.888 --> 14:50.454
share his doctoral committee, nor was I a member of 
it. But that's the relationship. In your 30 years,

